findings.recommendation:
Capture the rename outcome and branch the log message accordingly. Example:

```kotlin
val renamed = dbFile.renameTo(target)
if (!renamed) {
    // Rename failed; the sidecars and fresh build will still be attempted,
    // but record the true filesystem state so triage is not misled.
    runBlocking {
        errorLog.e(LOG_COMPONENT, "db open failed — rename to $corruptName FAILED", cause)
    }
} else {
    runBlocking {
        errorLog.e(LOG_COMPONENT, "db open failed — renamed to $corruptName", cause)
    }
}
```

Consider also deleting the corrupt `sanctum.db` as a last-resort fallback when rename fails, so the subsequent `buildSanctumDatabase` call is not guaranteed to re-hit the same corruption.

Before recursing, verify the entry is a regular directory and not a symlink. On API 26+ this is available via java.nio.file:

```kotlin
import java.nio.file.Files
import java.nio.file.LinkOption

private fun safeDelete(dir: File) {
    val path = dir.toPath()
    if (Files.isSymbolicLink(path) || !Files.isDirectory(path, LinkOption.NOFOLLOW_LINKS)) {
        // Refuse to recurse into a symlink; unlink the link itself only.
        Files.deleteIfExists(path)
        return
    }
    if (!dir.deleteRecursively()) {
        throw IOException("delete failed: ${dir.absolutePath}")
    }
}
```

Alternatively, keep `deleteRecursively()` but first assert `dir.canonicalPath.startsWith(attachmentsDir.canonicalPath + File.separator)` to refuse any entry whose canonical path escapes the intended root.

Either annotate with `@Volatile`:

```kotlin
@Singleton
class AppCorruptionState @Inject constructor() {
    @Volatile var corruptionOccurred: Boolean = false
}
```

or promote to `AtomicBoolean`, or expose as `MutableStateFlow<Boolean>` if the Task 10 consumer wants reactive observation. The first option is the smallest diff.
